			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The current ordering of IR passes (including ABI simplification passes) in pnacl-ld.py was chosen to be robust but it doesn't necessarily produce the best code.

e.g. '-nacl-expand-tls' runs before dead global elimination has the chance to remove unused TLS variables.

Jan suggests that '-expand-byval' should run after '-argpromotion' (which is part of -O3) since the latter can remove some byval arguments.  (See https://codereview.chromium.org/14317008/.)

Also, pnacl-ld.py currently invokes 'opt' upto three times, but this could be combined into a single invocation which would reduce time spent serialising and deserialising bitcode.
